<segment id="1" parent="1001" relname="preparation">Measure Market Volatility</segment>
<segment id="2" parent="1002" relname="span">Volatility in financial markets is a concern among finance professionals , traders and investors , and anybody else</segment>
<segment id="3" parent="2" relname="elaboration">looking at the ongoing market situation for a particular region or exchange .</segment>
<segment id="4" parent="1004" relname="span">But volatility is a word</segment>
<segment id="5" parent="4" relname="elaboration">that many individuals use in many different contexts .</segment>
<segment id="6" parent="1007" relname="condition">If you need to measure market volatility as an investor or anyone up with a stake in changes to a financial market ,</segment>
<segment id="7" parent="1008" relname="span">here are some of the best ways</segment>
<segment id="8" parent="7" relname="purpose">to examine volatility , or changes in market price ,</segment>
<segment id="9" parent="1008" relname="attribution">according to some experienced professionals and others .</segment>
<segment id="10" parent="1010" relname="preparation">Steps</segment>
<segment id="11" parent="1011" relname="span">Choose a time frame</segment>
<segment id="12" parent="11" relname="elaboration">in which to examine market volatility .</segment>
<segment id="13" parent="1013" relname="span">Volatility is a variable</segment>
<segment id="14" parent="13" relname="elaboration">that is only accurate within a certain time frame .</segment>
<segment id="15" parent="1015" relname="span">That 's why most brokerage accounts and other services provide time adjustable charts</segment>
<segment id="16" parent="17" relname="attribution">that show</segment>
<segment id="17" parent="1016" relname="span">how an asset , a market or a collection of financial products has changed over a specific amount of time .</segment>
<segment id="18" parent="1018" relname="span">Use formulas</segment>
<segment id="19" parent="18" relname="purpose">to further define volatility .</segment>
<segment id="20" parent="1020" relname="span">Within your given time frame , you can make use of simple or more complex formulas</segment>
<segment id="21" parent="20" relname="purpose">to calculate volatility technically .</segment>
<segment id="22" parent="1022" relname="span">Use an index</segment>
<segment id="23" parent="22" relname="elaboration">to look at how volatility has affected multiple assets .</segment>
<segment id="24" parent="1024" relname="contrast">Single stocks or financial products have their own specific volatility within a market ,</segment>
<segment id="25" parent="1025" relname="span">but traders often use an index</segment>
<segment id="26" parent="25" relname="purpose">to define volatility for multiple stocks or products .</segment>
<segment id="27" parent="1028" relname="span">An index is simply a collection of values for stocks , funds and other products</segment>
<segment id="28" parent="27" relname="elaboration">that provides a total change in price .</segment>
<segment id="29" parent="1030" relname="span">One of the most basic formulas</segment>
<segment id="30" parent="1031" relname="span">for calculating volatility is the following :</segment>
<segment id="31" parent="1033" relname="span">range</segment>
<segment id="32" parent="31" relname="elaboration">multiplied by ( maximum price minus minimum price )</segment>
<segment id="33" parent="1032" relname="same_unit">for your time period .</segment>
<segment id="34" parent="1029" relname="joint">Other more complex formulas like VIX or Beta help finance professionals and others understand more about how prices are changing within a given market .</segment>
<segment id="35" parent="1035" relname="span">Calculate percentage changes .</segment>
<segment id="36" parent="1037" relname="span">Using individual assets or the index tools</segment>
<segment id="37" parent="36" relname="elaboration">mentioned above ,</segment>
<segment id="38" parent="1038" relname="sequence">take a look at how much a price has changed over time</segment>
<segment id="39" parent="1039" relname="span">and calculate that as a percentage of the total value</segment>
<segment id="40" parent="1041" relname="span">to find a " total volatility "</segment>
<segment id="41" parent="40" relname="elaboration">that you can use</segment>
<segment id="42" parent="1041" relname="purpose">to predict future markets .</segment>
<segment id="43" parent="1043" relname="span">Assess various stock index tools</segment>
<segment id="44" parent="45" relname="attribution">to see</segment>
<segment id="45" parent="1044" relname="span">how they can help you measure volatility .</segment>
<segment id="46" parent="1046" relname="span">For example , in the American market , the Dow Jones industrial average , a collection of blue-chip stocks , has its own volatility calculations</segment>
<segment id="47" parent="1047" relname="span">that can help you better understand</segment>
<segment id="48" parent="47" relname="elaboration">where a market has been and where it is going .</segment>
<segment id="49" parent="1049" relname="preparation">Evaluate moving averages .</segment>
<segment id="50" parent="1050" relname="contrast">For many traders , it 's not enough just to see how much a price has changed .</segment>
<segment id="51" parent="1050" relname="contrast">It 's also important to see which direction that change has gone within a greater context .</segment>
<segment id="52" parent="1053" relname="condition">Even if you have identified your specific time frame for volatility ,</segment>
<segment id="53" parent="1053" relname="sequence">you may want to go back further</segment>
<segment id="54" parent="1053" relname="sequence">and look at how the stock or other asset has changed over a greater time frame .</segment>
<segment id="55" parent="1055" relname="span">A moving average helps financial professionals to do this</segment>
<segment id="56" parent="55" relname="means">by providing an average price for the asset over a longer period of time such as 1 year .</segment>
<segment id="57" parent="1054" relname="joint">Account for market sentiments .</segment>
<segment id="58" parent="1054" relname="joint">Use random number method like Random Number tables or concept of ' Brownian Motion for financial analysis ' especially in case of Stock market volatility .</segment>
